Title:
Initial Access: Modern Intrusion Techniques (The Art of Getting In)

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- A red-team–oriented guide to achieving initial access (MITRE ATT&CK TA0001) with a phased approach covering payload delivery, phishing, MFA bypass, credential attacks, exploitation, vishing, physical access, and supply-chain/trusted-relationship compromise.  
- It focuses on practical tradecraft for getting code execution or valid credentials while evading common controls like email gateways, SmartScreen/MOTW, AMSI, and EDR.  
- Techniques discussed include container-based MOTW bypass (VHD/VHDX/IMG), HTML smuggling, code-signing/reputation considerations, DLL sideloading discovery with Procmon, LNK-based execution, and modern shellcode loader patterns (RW→RX, section mapping, direct/indirect syscalls).  
- It also covers identity-centric access paths such as Evilginx-style adversary-in-the-middle token theft, OAuth device-code phishing, password spraying/stuffing with IP rotation, and Teams/QR (“quishing”) delivery.  
- Real-world case studies (APT29, Scattered Spider, Lazarus, Cl0p/MOVEit, SolarWinds) are used to anchor the techniques and OPSEC guidance.  
- Most useful for red teamers and pentesters designing initial access playbooks; also valuable to blue teams for understanding attacker chains and detection points.

Technical Focus:
- Mark-of-the-Web (Zone.Identifier ADS) bypass via containers (VHD/VHDX/IMG/ISO)
- HTML smuggling (client-side payload assembly in browser)
- SmartScreen reputation and code-signing/metadata cloning
- DLL sideloading (Windows DLL search order, Procmon “NAME NOT FOUND” hunting)
- EDR-evasive loaders (RW→RX, NtCreateSection/NtMapViewOfSection, direct syscalls/ETW/AMSI evasion)
- MFA bypass/token theft (Evilginx AitM, OAuth device code phishing)

Use Cases:
- Build a phishing delivery chain that reduces gateway/sandbox/SmartScreen friction
- Execute payloads via signed-binary + DLL sideloading to blend with trusted processes
- Run token-theft campaigns against M365 with AitM or device-code OAuth flows
- Perform controlled password spraying/stuffing with enumeration and IP rotation
- Prioritize initial access vectors using a decision matrix (exposed apps vs. identity vs. physical)
- Map initial access TTPs to MITRE ATT&CK for reporting and defensive validation

Keywords:
Initial Access, MITRE ATT&CK TA0001, T1566, phishing, spearphishing, HTML smuggling, Mark-of-the-Web, Zone.Identifier, SmartScreen, VHD, VHDX, ISO, DLL sideloading, Procmon, LNK, AMSI, ETW, direct syscalls, NtCreateSection, NtMapViewOfSection, Evilginx, adversary-in-the-middle, OAuth device code phishing, Microsoft 365, password spraying, o365spray, CredMaster, fireprox, Teams phishing, quishing, CVE-2023-34362, MOVEit, supply chain compromise